target_title: Menu : About Sudoku->Credits - pops under playing board grid on left/right

note.body:
See if you can reproduce it on the [flatpak version](https://flathub.org/apps/org.gnome.Sudoku). 

Nothing changed between v46 and v47 regarding gridlines in GNOME Sudoku, it's most likely a problem coming from the dependencies. 

You are free to theme the application however you want, but be aware that those themes are not supported here or upstream, meaning if you run into issues, you're on your own.

target_title: Menu : About Sudoku->Credits - pops under playing board grid on left/right

note.body:
I appreciate you explaining that the only theme supported is libadwaita. I though you were able to theme Gtk apps. I've tried the `Adwaita-dark` theme and the playing board shows the same washed-out look with no gridlines, e.g.

> Did you enable the "Number Picker On Second Click" Option? You're describing exactly what's it's intended to do.

The number picker is just to show the theme issue. The issue with the disregard of the first mouse click is having to click twice on the `Start Game` button before gnome-sudoku does anything.

target_title: Menu : About Sudoku->Credits - pops under playing board grid on left/right

note.body:
3 isssues, 3 threads please. This is a pain to handle and close. I'll be closing this, feel free to post new threads that address what you think are still issues.    

1. This issue is almost certainly not a GNOME Sudoku issue. GNOME Sudoku isn't doing anything special here, it's a regular adwaita preferences widget. Report this to your package maintainer. 
2. Themes other than adwaita are not supported. Report this issue to your theme provider. 
3. Did you enable the "Number Picker On Second Click" Option? You're describing exactly what's it's intended to do.

note.body:
I wasn't aware that this affected the buttons too, but it makes sense. By the way this is unrelated to the accent colors, it's about the css rules overriding the defaults when they shouldn't be. 

If you have other issues, particularly in light mode and using the [development version](https://gitlab.gnome.org/GNOME/gnome-sudoku#getting-gnome-sudoku), do let me know.
